## What happened

Apple's security frameworks (`Security.framework` / `CommonCrypto`) **dropped DSA support**. .NET on macOS uses these native frameworks for cryptography. Starting in .NET 11, `DSA.Create()` throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** on macOS because the underlying OS primitive is no longer available. (On Linux/Windows, DSA still works via OpenSSL and CNG respectively.)

## How to fix it

Since you only need to **verify** legacy signatures (not create new ones), you have two practical options:

### Option 1 — Use BouncyCastle (recommended)

```bash
dotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography
```

```csharp
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Security;

bool VerifyDsaSignature(byte[] data, byte[] signature, DsaPublicKeyParameters publicKey)
{
    var signer = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA1withDSA");
    signer.Init(forSigning: false, publicKey);
    signer.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);
    return signer.VerifySignature(signature);
}
```

This is a fully managed implementation — no OS dependency, works everywhere.

### Option 2 — Use OpenSSL on macOS via P/Invoke

Install OpenSSL (`brew install openssl`) and interop with it directly. This is more fragile and harder to maintain.

## Longer-term recommendation

DSA is a **legacy algorithm** (FIPS 186-4 recommends ECDSA or EdDSA). If you control the signature format, migrate to **ECDSA** (`ECDsa.Create()`), which is supported on all platforms natively in .NET.
